The paper deals with lower bounds for polynomial calculus and polynomial calculus resolution, which are topics in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The techniques used involve graph theory and clustering, which are also relevant to data structures (cs.DS) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also discusses the functional pigeonhole principle, which is a topic in logic and set theory (cs.LO), and uses expander graphs, which are a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
